Any living language is constantly changing [http://www.infoplease.com/ce6/society/A0858000.html] with words developing as the need arises.  The word polylogue comes from the words [[poly]] and [[dialogue]].
One concept is that for a number of threads of conversation, such as occurs on a blog or wiki site, the word polylogue more correctly expresses the communication that occurs.  A number of dialogues occur simultaneously, hence the composite term, polylogue. There is a peer reviewed article where it is used [http://crg.polytechnique.fr/publications/popup.php?idtitrebase=617&LangueInterface=EN], another article on its definition and alt defs [http://www.inst.at/studies/s_0802_e.htm], an article where it's used as per the definition presented [http://www.utdallas.edu/pretext/PT1.1A/PT1.1A.html], and its even used as early as 1961 in [http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/entrez/query.fcgi?cmd=Retrieve&db=PubMed&list_uids=13695027&dopt=Abstract The Lancet], although it probably was a neologism then.